{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17539624","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17539624"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:44:42+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:44:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16689"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16689","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16689"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.51,0.42,0.02,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9380"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109448"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9380","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9380"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16689"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91813"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"688"},{"type":"tags","id":"1713"},{"type":"tags","id":"2047"},{"type":"tags","id":"2746"},{"type":"tags","id":"4072"},{"type":"tags","id":"4192"},{"type":"tags","id":"4193"},{"type":"tags","id":"4194"},{"type":"tags","id":"4195"},{"type":"tags","id":"4197"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"10950"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"12801"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22197"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40885"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43639"},{"type":"contributions","id":"47406"},{"type":"contributions","id":"49751"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109448","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109448"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 22-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a nine-month history of absent menstrual periods. She previously had regular periods since menarche at age 13. She reports feeling increasingly tired and has gained 8 kg over the past year despite no changes to her diet. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She is sexually active and uses condoms for contraception.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 62/min, blood pressure 118/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 14/min, SpO2 99% on room air, and temperature 36.5\u00b0C. Her BMI is 28 kg/m2 with a weight of 72kg. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPregnancy test: negative\u003Cbr /\u003EThyroid stimulating hormone: 15.2 mU/L (0.4-4.0)\u003Cbr /\u003EFree thyroxine: 8 pmol/L (10-20)\u003Cbr /\u003EProlactin: 450 mU/L (100-500)\u003Cbr /\u003EFollicle stimulating hormone: 4.2 IU/L (3.5-12.5)\u003Cbr /\u003ELuteinizing hormone: 3.8 IU/L (2.4-12.6)\u003Cbr /\u003EDay 21 progesterone: \u0026lt;1 nmol/L (\u0026gt;30)\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Clomiphene citrate","Levothyroxine 25 micrograms daily","Levothyroxine 100 micrograms daily","Combined oral contraceptive pill","Bromocriptine"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with secondary amenorrhoea and symptoms suggestive of hypothyroidism, confirmed by elevated TSH and low free thyroxine levels. The normal prolactin and gonadotropins, along with low day 21 progesterone, indicate anovulation secondary to hypothyroidism rather than other causes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELevothyroxine 25 micrograms daily\u003C/strong\u003E would be too low a starting dose for this patient. While some patients require gradual dose escalation, this patient is young and otherwise healthy, allowing for a standard starting dose.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELevothyroxine 100 micrograms daily\u003C/strong\u003E is the appropriate starting dose for primary hypothyroidism in young, otherwise healthy adults (generally 1.6 \u00b5g per kilogram body weight). This dose should normalise thyroid function and resolve the amenorrhoea. TSH should be checked after 6-8 weeks to adjust the dose if needed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECombined oral contraceptive pill\u003C/strong\u003E would induce withdrawal bleeds but would not address the underlying thyroid dysfunction causing the amenorrhoea. It would also mask whether thyroid replacement has successfully restored normal menstrual function.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EClomiphene citrate\u003C/strong\u003E is used to induce ovulation in anovulatory women trying to conceive. It would be inappropriate before correcting the thyroid dysfunction and is not indicated as this patient is not trying to conceive.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBromocriptine\u003C/strong\u003E is used to treat hyperprolactinaemia, which is not present in this case as evidenced by the normal prolactin level.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe approach to secondary amenorrhoea requires systematic investigation including pregnancy test, thyroid function, prolactin, and gonadotropins. The low day 21 progesterone confirms anovulation. Hypothyroidism is a reversible cause that should be treated before considering other interventions. Regular monitoring of thyroid function is essential to ensure adequate replacement.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Secondary amenorrhoea requires systematic investigation including pregnancy, thyroid function, prolactin, and gonadotropins.","Hypothyroidism is a reversible cause of secondary amenorrhoea that should be treated with levothyroxine."],"references":["Osmosis. Secondary Amenorrhea [Internet]. [cited 2024 Nov 29]. Available from: https://www.osmosis.org/answers/secondary-amenorrhea","Ward R, Stuart P. Hypothyroidism [Internet]. Aust Fam Physician. 2012 Aug [cited 2024 Nov 29];41(8):556-62. Available from: https://www.racgp.org.au/afp/2012/august/hypothyroidism"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91813"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16689"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91813","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/91813"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-21T13:29:47+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-21T13:36:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9380"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109448"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II",